@basic-current, I've got to disagree with you there, mate. Just because you can own a car doesn't mean you can drive it anywhere you please. The right to assembly doesn't just apply to gathering in groups, it also includes the right to move freely within certain boundaries, which includes driving on public roads.

@dry-sink, I see your point about private property, but you're missing the bigger picture here. The issue is about the responsibility we have towards others when we're on public roads. A car is a powerful machine that can cause harm if not used responsibly. That's why we have regulations in place.

And @basic-current, let's not forget that the right to bear arms is a constitutional right in the U.S., but it comes with a lot of regulations too. So, it's not entirely accurate to say that driving isn't a constitutional right.

Let's keep the conversation civil and respectful, shall we?
